\title{Aflpp}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{AFL++ is a fork of AFL with better fuzzing performance and advanced features. Use for multi-core fuzzing of C/C++ projects.}

\subtree{
\title{AFL++}
\p{AFL++ is a fork of the original AFL fuzzer that offers better fuzzing performance and more advanced features while maintaining stability. A major benefit over libFuzzer is that AFL++ has stable support for running fuzzing campaigns on multiple cores, making it ideal for large-scale fuzzing efforts.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use}
\pre{\startverb
| Fuzzer | Best For | Complexity |
|--------|----------|------------|
| AFL++ | Multi-core fuzzing, diverse mutations, mature projects | Medium |
| libFuzzer | Quick setup, single-threaded, simple harnesses | Low |
| LibAFL | Custom fuzzers, research, advanced use cases | High |
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Choose AFL++ when:}}

\ul{
\li{You need multi-core fuzzing to maximize throughput}
\li{Your project can be compiled with Clang or GCC}
\li{You want diverse mutation strategies and mature tooling}
\li{libFuzzer has plateaued and you need more coverage}
\li{You're fuzzing production codebases that benefit from parallel execution}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Quick Start}
\pre{\startverb
extern "C" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    // Call your code with fuzzer-provided data
    check_buf((char*)data, size);
    return 0;
}
\stopverb}

\p{Compile and run:}

\pre{\startverb
# Setup AFL++ wrapper script first (see Installation)
./afl++ docker afl-clang-fast++ -DNO_MAIN=1 -O2 -fsanitize=fuzzer harness.cc main.cc -o fuzz
mkdir seeds && echo "aaaa" > seeds/minimal_seed
./afl++ docker afl-fuzz -i seeds -o out -- ./fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Installation}
\p{AFL++ has many dependencies including LLVM, Python, and Rust. We recommend using a current Debian or Ubuntu distribution for fuzzing with AFL++.}

\pre{\startverb
| Method | When to Use | Supported Compilers |
|--------|-------------|---------------------|
| Ubuntu/Debian repos | Recent Ubuntu, basic features only | Ubuntu 23.10: Clang 14 & GCC 13<br>Debian 12: Clang 14 & GCC 12 |
| Docker (from Docker Hub) | Specific AFL++ version, Apple Silicon support | As of 4.35c: Clang 19 & GCC 11 |
| Docker (from source) | Test unreleased features, apply patches | Configurable in Dockerfile |
| From source | Avoid Docker, need specific patches | Adjustable via `LLVM_CONFIG` env var |
\stopverb}

\subtree{
\title{Ubuntu/Debian}
\p{Prior to installing afl++, check the clang version dependency of the packge with \code{\startverb apt-cache show afl++\stopverb}, and install the matching \code{\startverb lld\stopverb} version (e.g., \code{\startverb lld-17\stopverb}).}

\pre{\startverb
apt install afl++ lld-17
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Docker (from Docker Hub)}
\pre{\startverb
docker pull aflplusplus/aflplusplus:stable
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Docker (from source)}
\pre{\startverb
git clone --depth 1 --branch stable https://github.com/AFLplusplus/AFLplusplus
cd AFLplusplus
docker build -t aflplusplus .
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{From source}
\p{Refer to the [Dockerfile](https://github.com/AFLplusplus/AFLplusplus/blob/stable/Dockerfile) for Ubuntu version requirements and dependencies. Set \code{\startverb LLVM_CONFIG\stopverb} to specify Clang version (e.g., \code{\startverb llvm-config-18\stopverb}).}
}

\subtree{
\title{Wrapper Script Setup}
\p{Create a wrapper script to run AFL++ on host or Docker:}

\pre{\startverb
cat <<'EOF' > ./afl++
#!/bin/sh
AFL_VERSION="${AFL_VERSION:-"stable"}"
case "$1" in
   host)
        shift
        bash -c "$*"
        ;;
    docker)
        shift
        /usr/bin/env docker run -ti \
            --privileged \
            -v ./:/src \
            --rm \
            --name afl_fuzzing \
            "aflplusplus/aflplusplus:$AFL_VERSION" \
            bash -c "cd /src && bash -c \"$*\""
        ;;
    *)
        echo "Usage: $0 {host|docker}"
        exit 1
        ;;
esac
EOF
chmod +x ./afl++
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Security Warning:} The \code{\startverb afl-system-config\stopverb} and \code{\startverb afl-persistent-config\stopverb} scripts require root privileges and disable OS security features. Do not fuzz on production systems or your development environment. Use a dedicated VM instead.}
}

\subtree{
\title{System Configuration}
\p{Run after each reboot for up to 15\% more executions per second:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-system-config
\stopverb}

\p{For maximum performance, disable kernel security mitigations (requires grub bootloader, not supported in Docker):}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ host afl-persistent-config
update-grub
reboot
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-system-config
\stopverb}

\p{Verify with \code{\startverb cat /proc/cmdline\stopverb} - output should include \code{\startverb mitigations=off\stopverb}.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Writing a Harness}
\subtree{
\title{Harness Structure}
\p{AFL++ supports libFuzzer-style harnesses:}

\pre{\startverb
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

extern "C" int LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput(const uint8_t *data, size_t size) {
    // 1. Validate input size if needed
    if (size < MIN_SIZE || size > MAX_SIZE) return 0;

    // 2. Call target function with fuzz data
    target_function(data, size);

    // 3. Return 0 (non-zero reserved for future use)
    return 0;
}
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Harness Rules}
\pre{\startverb
| Do | Don't |
|----|-------|
| Reset global state between runs | Rely on state from previous runs |
| Handle edge cases gracefully | Exit on invalid input |
| Keep harness deterministic | Use random number generators |
| Free allocated memory | Create memory leaks |
| Validate input sizes | Process unbounded input |
\stopverb}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For detailed harness writing techniques, patterns for handling complex inputs, and advanced strategies, see the \strong{fuzz-harness-writing} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Compilation}
\p{AFL++ offers multiple compilation modes with different trade-offs.}

\subtree{
\title{Compilation Mode Decision Tree}
\p{Choose your compilation mode:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{LTO mode} (\code{\startverb afl-clang-lto\stopverb}): Best performance and instrumentation. Try this first.}
\li{\strong{LLVM mode} (\code{\startverb afl-clang-fast\stopverb}): Fall back if LTO fails to compile.}
\li{\strong{GCC plugin} (\code{\startverb afl-gcc-fast\stopverb}): For projects requiring GCC.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Basic Compilation (LLVM mode)}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-clang-fast++ -DNO_MAIN=1 -O2 -fsanitize=fuzzer harness.cc main.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{GCC Compilation}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-g++-fast -DNO_MAIN=1 -O2 -fsanitize=fuzzer harness.cc main.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Important:} GCC version must match the version used to compile the AFL++ GCC plugin.}
}

\subtree{
\title{With Sanitizers}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> AFL_USE_ASAN=1 afl-clang-fast++ -DNO_MAIN=1 -O2 -fsanitize=fuzzer harness.cc main.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For detailed sanitizer configuration, common issues, and advanced flags, see the \strong{address-sanitizer} and \strong{undefined-behavior-sanitizer} technique skills.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Build Flags}
\p{Note that \code{\startverb -g\stopverb} is not necessary, it is added by default by the AFL++ compilers.}

\pre{\startverb
| Flag | Purpose |
|------|---------|
| `-DNO_MAIN=1` | Skip main function when using libFuzzer harness |
| `-O2` | Production optimization level (recommended for fuzzing) |
| `-fsanitize=fuzzer` | Enable libFuzzer compatibility mode and adds the fuzzer runtime when linking executable |
| `-fsanitize=fuzzer-no-link` | Instrument without linking fuzzer runtime (for static libraries and object files) |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Corpus Management}
\subtree{
\title{Creating Initial Corpus}
\p{AFL++ requires at least one non-empty seed file:}

\pre{\startverb
mkdir seeds
echo "aaaa" > seeds/minimal_seed
\stopverb}

\p{For real projects, gather representative inputs:}

\ul{
\li{Download example files for the format you're fuzzing}
\li{Extract test cases from the project's test suite}
\li{Use minimal valid inputs for your file format}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Corpus Minimization}
\p{After a campaign, minimize the corpus to keep only unique coverage:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-cmin -i out/default/queue -o minimized_corpus -- ./fuzz
\stopverb}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For corpus creation strategies, dictionaries, and seed selection, see the \strong{fuzzing-corpus} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Running Campaigns}
\subtree{
\title{Basic Run}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -i seeds -o out -- ./fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Setting Environment Variables}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> AFL_FAST_CAL=1 afl-fuzz -i seeds -o out -- ./fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Interpreting Output}
\p{The AFL++ UI shows real-time fuzzing statistics:}

\pre{\startverb
| Output | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| **execs/sec** | Execution speed - higher is better |
| **cycles done** | Number of queue passes completed |
| **corpus count** | Number of unique test cases in queue |
| **saved crashes** | Number of unique crashes found |
| **stability** | % of stable edges (should be near 100%) |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Output Directory Structure}
\pre{\startverb
out/default/
├── cmdline          # How was the SUT invoked?
├── crashes/         # Inputs that crash the SUT
│   └── id:000000,sig:06,src:000002,time:286,execs:13105,op:havoc,rep:4
├── hangs/           # Inputs that hang the SUT
├── queue/           # Test cases reproducing final fuzzer state
│   ├── id:000000,time:0,execs:0,orig:minimal_seed
│   └── id:000001,src:000000,time:0,execs:8,op:havoc,rep:6,+cov
├── fuzzer_stats     # Campaign statistics
└── plot_data        # Data for plotting
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Analyzing Results}
\p{View live campaign statistics:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-whatsup out
\stopverb}

\p{Create coverage plots:}

\pre{\startverb
apt install gnuplot
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-plot out/default out_graph/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Re-executing Test Cases}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> ./fuzz out/default/crashes/<test_case>
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Fuzzer Options}
\pre{\startverb
| Option | Purpose |
|--------|---------|
| `-G 4000` | Maximum test input length (default: 1048576 bytes) |
| `-t 1000` | Timeout in milliseconds for each test case (default: 1000ms) |
| `-m 1000` | Memory limit in megabytes (default: 0 = unlimited) |
| `-x ./dict.dict` | Use dictionary file to guide mutations |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Environment Variables That Matter}
\p{AFL++ has [many environment variables](https://aflplus.plus/docs/env_variables/), but most are niche. These are the ones that matter in practice.}

\subtree{
\title{Always Set These}
\pre{\startverb
# Every campaign should use tmpfs — SSDs will thank you, and it's faster
AFL_TMPDIR=/dev/shm
\stopverb}

\p{\code{\startverb AFL_TMPDIR\stopverb} is a free performance win with no downsides — not setting it wears out your SSD and slows fuzzing.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Slow Targets}
\pre{\startverb
# Speeds up calibration ~2.5x — use when targets are slow (e.g., >10 ms/exec)
AFL_FAST_CAL=1
\stopverb}

\p{\code{\startverb AFL_FAST_CAL\stopverb} reduces calibration time with negligible precision loss. Recommended specifically for slow targets where calibration would otherwise take a long time.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Multi-Core Campaigns}
\pre{\startverb
# On the primary (-M) instance only — needed for afl-cmin, not for fuzzing itself
AFL_FINAL_SYNC=1

# On all instances — cache test cases in memory (default: 50 MB, good range: 50-250 MB)
AFL_TESTCACHE_SIZE=100
\stopverb}

\p{\code{\startverb AFL_FINAL_SYNC\stopverb} tells the primary instance to do a final import from all secondaries when stopping. This does not affect the fuzzing process itself — it only matters when you later run \code{\startverb afl-cmin\stopverb} for corpus minimization, ensuring the primary's queue has the full combined corpus. \code{\startverb AFL_TESTCACHE_SIZE\stopverb} caches test cases in memory to reduce disk I/O; the default is 50 MB and values between 50-250 MB work well for most campaigns.}
}

\subtree{
\title{CI/Automated Fuzzing}
\pre{\startverb
# Fail fast if fuzzing isn't finding anything
AFL_EXIT_ON_TIME=3600  # 1 hour with no new paths = stop

# Or run until "done" (all queue entries processed)
AFL_EXIT_WHEN_DONE=1

# Headless environments
AFL_NO_UI=1
\stopverb}

\p{Unbounded fuzzing in CI wastes resources. Set time limits or use exit conditions.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Variables to Avoid}
\pre{\startverb
| Variable | Why Skip It |
|----------|-------------|
| `AFL_NO_ARITH` | Can hurt coverage on binary formats, but may be useful for text-based targets |
| `AFL_SHUFFLE_QUEUE` | Only for exotic setups, usually harmful |
| `AFL_DISABLE_TRIM` | Trimming is valuable, don't disable without reason |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Multi-Core Fuzzing}
\p{AFL++ excels at multi-core fuzzing with two major advantages:}

\ol{
\li{More executions per second (scales linearly with physical cores)}
\li{Asymmetrical fuzzing (e.g., one ASan job, rest without sanitizers)}
}

\subtree{
\title{Starting a Campaign}
\p{Start the primary fuzzer (in background):}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -M primary -i seeds -o state -- ./fuzz 1>primary.log 2>primary.error &
\stopverb}

\p{Start secondary fuzzers (as many as you have cores):}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -S secondary01 -i seeds -o state -- ./fuzz 1>secondary01.log 2>secondary01.error &
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -S secondary02 -i seeds -o state -- ./fuzz 1>secondary02.log 2>secondary02.error &
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Monitoring Multi-Core Campaigns}
\p{List all running jobs:}

\pre{\startverb
jobs
\stopverb}

\p{View live statistics (updates every second):}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> watch -n1 --color afl-whatsup state/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Stopping All Fuzzers}
\pre{\startverb
kill $(jobs -p)
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Coverage Analysis}
\p{AFL++ automatically tracks coverage through edge instrumentation. Coverage information is stored in \code{\startverb fuzzer_stats\stopverb} and \code{\startverb plot_data\stopverb}.}

\subtree{
\title{Measuring Coverage}
\p{Use \code{\startverb afl-plot\stopverb} to visualize coverage over time:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-plot out/default out_graph/
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Improving Coverage}
\ul{
\li{Use dictionaries for format-aware fuzzing}
\li{Run longer campaigns (cycles_wo_finds indicates plateau)}
\li{Try different mutation strategies with multi-core fuzzing}
\li{Analyze coverage gaps and add targeted seed inputs}
}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For detailed coverage analysis techniques, identifying coverage gaps, and systematic coverage improvement, see the \strong{coverage-analysis} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{CMPLOG}
\p{CMPLOG/RedQueen is the best path constraint solving mechanism available in any fuzzer. To enable it, the fuzz target needs to be instrumented for it. Before building the fuzzing target set the environment variable:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> AFL_LLVM_CMPLOG=1 make
\stopverb}

\p{No special action is needed for compiling and linking the harness.}

\p{To run a fuzzer instance with a CMPLOG instrumented fuzzing target, add \code{\startverb -c0\stopverb} to the command like arguments:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -c0 -S cmplog -i seeds -o state -- ./fuzz 1>secondary02.log 2>secondary02.error &
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Sanitizer Integration}
\p{Sanitizers are essential for finding memory corruption bugs that don't cause immediate crashes.}

\subtree{
\title{AddressSanitizer (ASan)}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> AFL_USE_ASAN=1 afl-clang-fast++ -DNO_MAIN=1 -O2 -fsanitize=fuzzer harness.cc main.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}

\p{\strong{Note:} Memory limit (\code{\startverb -m\stopverb}) is not supported with ASan due to 20TB virtual memory reservation.}
}

\subtree{
\title{UndefinedBehaviorSanitizer (UBSan)}
\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> AFL_USE_UBSAN=1 afl-clang-fast++ -DNO_MAIN=1 -O2 -fsanitize=fuzzer,undefined harness.cc main.cc -o fuzz
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Common Sanitizer Issues}
\pre{\startverb
| Issue | Solution |
|-------|----------|
| ASan slows fuzzing | Use only 1 ASan job in multi-core setup |
| Stack exhaustion | Increase stack with `ASAN_OPTIONS=stack_size=...` |
| GCC version mismatch | Ensure system GCC matches AFL++ plugin version |
\stopverb}

\blockquote{\strong{See Also:} For comprehensive sanitizer configuration and troubleshooting, see the \strong{address-sanitizer} technique skill.}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Advanced Usage}
\subtree{
\title{Tips and Tricks}
\pre{\startverb
| Tip | Why It Helps |
|-----|--------------|
| Use LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput harnesses where possible | If a fuzzing campaign has at least 85% stability then this is the most efficient fuzzing style. If not then try standard input or file input fuzzing |
| Use dictionaries | Helps fuzzer discover format-specific keywords and magic bytes |
| Set realistic timeouts | Prevents false positives from system load |
| Limit input size | Larger inputs don't necessarily explore more space |
| Monitor stability | Low stability indicates non-deterministic behavior |
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Standard Input Fuzzing}
\p{AFL++ can fuzz programs reading from stdin without a libFuzzer harness:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-clang-fast++ -O2 main_stdin.c -o fuzz_stdin
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -i seeds -o out -- ./fuzz_stdin
\stopverb}

\p{This is slower than persistent mode but requires no harness code.}
}

\subtree{
\title{File Input Fuzzing}
\p{For programs that read files, use \code{\startverb @@\stopverb} placeholder:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-clang-fast++ -O2 main_file.c -o fuzz_file
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -i seeds -o out -- ./fuzz_file @@
\stopverb}

\p{For better performance, use \code{\startverb fmemopen\stopverb} to create file descriptors from memory.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Argument Fuzzing}
\p{Fuzz command-line arguments using \code{\startverb argv-fuzz-inl.h\stopverb}:}

\pre{\startverb
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

#ifdef __AFL_COMPILER
#include "argv-fuzz-inl.h"
#endif

void check_buf(char *buf, size_t buf_len) {
    if(buf_len > 0 && buf[0] == 'a') {
        if(buf_len > 1 && buf[1] == 'b') {
            if(buf_len > 2 && buf[2] == 'c') {
                abort();
            }
        }
    }
}

int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
#ifdef __AFL_COMPILER
    AFL_INIT_ARGV();
#endif

    if (argc < 2) {
        fprintf(stderr, "Usage: %s <input_string>\n", argv[0]);
        return 1;
    }

    char *input_buf = argv[1];
    size_t len = strlen(input_buf);
    check_buf(input_buf, len);
    return 0;
}
\stopverb}

\p{Download the header:}

\pre{\startverb
curl -O https://raw.githubusercontent.com/AFLplusplus/AFLplusplus/stable/utils/argv_fuzzing/argv-fuzz-inl.h
\stopverb}

\p{Compile and run:}

\pre{\startverb
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-clang-fast++ -O2 main_arg.c -o fuzz_arg
./afl++ <host/docker> afl-fuzz -i seeds -o out -- ./fuzz_arg
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Performance Tuning}
\pre{\startverb
| Setting | Impact |
|---------|--------|
| CPU core count | Linear scaling with physical cores |
| Persistent mode | 10-20x faster than fork server |
| `-G` input size limit | Smaller = faster, but may miss bugs |
| ASan ratio | 1 ASan job per 4-8 non-ASan jobs |
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Troubleshooting}
\pre{\startverb
| Problem | Cause | Solution |
|---------|-------|----------|
| Low exec/sec (<1k) | Not using persistent mode | Create a LLVMFuzzerTestOneInput style harness |
| Low stability (<85%) | Non-deterministic code | Fuzz a program via stdin or file inputs, or create such a harness |
| GCC plugin error | GCC version mismatch | Ensure system GCC matches AFL++ build and install gcc-$GCC_VERSION-plugin-dev |
| No crashes found | Need sanitizers | Recompile with `AFL_USE_ASAN=1` |
| Memory limit exceeded | ASan uses 20TB virtual | Remove `-m` flag when using ASan |
| Docker performance loss | Virtualization overhead | Use bare metal or VM for production fuzzing |
\stopverb}
}

